{\setlength\leftmargini{1.0em} \setlength\leftmarginii{0.5em}
\begin{enumerate}
\item 
d94 15
d110 8
a117 3
Range and Duration
\begin{enumerate}
\setlength\itemsep{0pt}
d119 6
a124 48
  Wall of Bones.  Range is line of sight (the targets view - if not
  facing it then is not affected until such time as target does face
  it).  Once viewed, facing is no longer important, that is if target
  turns to run from the wall then does not lose fear because they are
  no longer facing it.  The target will remain affected until out of
  line of sight of the wall.  Duration is that of the spell - once
  wall is gone, so is the fear.

  \begin{enumerate}
  \setlength\itemsep{0pt}
  \item
    Target panics and runs away from the wall around a corner. They
    are now out of line of sight and are not affected by the fear. If
    they should go back around the corner and the wall is still
    standing, they will simply panic again. However, if their
    resistance has changed, eg. bv a suitable counterspell, the wall
    is treated as a different one and a new resistance check is made,
    a new roll on the fright table being made if needed.

    \item
    Target immobilised ctc. WP rolls made as per table.  Once snapped
    out of it, the target has a pulse to act, the effect of the wall
    occurring after actions have been decided. If the target looks at
    the wall again the same fright table roll applies. If resistance
    has changed treat as above.
  \end{enumerate}
  \item Mass Fear
  Has set range and duration.  Range is a sphere around the
  adept. Targets going out of range are treated as for wall of bones.
  If immobilised, etc.  once snapped out of it the spell has no
  further effect other than that described in the appropriate table
  description.

  \item Spell of Fear with ``immediate'' duration - Celestial and Black
  colleges.  After (rank of spell / 5) pulses, rounded up, the target
  may begin making WP rolls (once times) to spell it has no further
  effect. Note that recovery may require 2 WP checks.  This can occur
  for the effects of 91--95 and 96--100 since on recovering from the
  initial effect the target may need to recover from the secondary
  effect.  The range of the spell defines the maximum distance from
  Adept to target for tje spell to work. Moving outside that range
  once the spell has had an effect will not stop the spell's workings.

  \item Spell of fear with ``concentration'' duration -- Necromantic
  College.  This spell has a set range which means it functions like a
  mass fear, but affects only one target.  Passive concentration is
  required -- stunning etc. will break the spell.
  \end{enumerate}
